# NestJS Conventions

## Module Structure

```
src/
  modules/
    <feature>/
      <feature>.module.ts
      <feature>.controller.ts
      <feature>.service.ts
      <feature>.repository.ts
      interfaces/
      dto/
      guards/
```

## Single Responsibility per Service

Each service handles ONE domain concern. Never mix responsibilities.

```typescript
// BAD — mixed concerns
@Injectable()
class UserService {
  createUser() { /* ... */ }
  sendWelcomeEmail() { /* ... */ }
  generateReport() { /* ... */ }
}

// GOOD — separated
@Injectable()
class UserService { createUser() { /* ... */ } }
@Injectable()
class NotificationService { sendWelcomeEmail() { /* ... */ } }
@Injectable()
class ReportService { generateReport() { /* ... */ } }
```

## Layer Responsibilities

| Layer | Responsibility |
|-------|---------------|
| Controller | HTTP handling, validation, response shaping |
| Service | Business logic, orchestration |
| Repository | Data access, query building |

- Controllers NEVER access repositories directly
- Services NEVER handle HTTP concerns (request/response objects)
- Repositories NEVER contain business logic

## DTOs & Validation

- Use `class-validator` + `class-transformer` for all DTOs
- Separate `CreateDto`, `UpdateDto`, `ResponseDto` per entity
- NEVER expose internal entities in API responses
